Cordova and Server
--------------------------

I notice that in your javascript code you do not give an IP address when you call AJAX

    url: &quot;[NO IP HERE]js/DBcall.php&quot;,

A cordova application is its own web server and therefore cannot attach remote PHP code without IP. It therefore needs the IP of your server (i.e. your computer) to be able to reach it.

If you are on the same network, you must prefix with your local ip :

    url: &quot;192.168.1.5/js/DBcall.php&quot;,

## Val is undefined ##

You can see : `dataType: &#39;json&#39;` so in fact, you&#39;r `val` object will be a json string.

You don&#39;t give me enough detail, so I&#39;m going to extrapolate a little bit.
Let&#39;s say you want to send two variable to the server: cat and dog 

You&#39;re going to have a code that looks like this:

    data : JSON.stringify({ cat: MyCatValue, dog: MyDogValue })

Your PHP code is from the 80s.
------------------------------
Sorry to say this but in my opinion the tutorial you went to see must be old enough.

To contact a MySQL database in PHP I advise you to use PDO2 like this : 

    $host = &#39;localhost&#39;;
    $dbname = &#39;MY_DB_NAME&#39;;
    $user = &#39;root&#39;;
    $pass = &#39;&#39;;
    
    try {
        $dbh = new PDO(&quot;mysql:host=$host;dbname=$dbname&quot;, $user, $pass);
        
        $stmt = $dbh-&gt;prepare(&quot;INSERT INTO animals ( dogName, catName ) values ( :dogName, :catName )&quot;);
        $stmt-&gt;bindParam(&#39;:dogName&#39;, $dogName);
        $stmt-&gt;bindParam(&#39;:catName&#39;, $catName);
        
        $dogName = &#39;foo&#39;;
        $catName = &#39;bar&#39;;
        $stmt-&gt;execute();
        
        $dbh = null;
    } catch (PDOException $e) {
        file_put_contents(&#39;error_log.txt&#39;, $e-&gt;getMessage() . PHP_EOL, FILE_APPEND);
    }

## Be carefull##

isn&#39;t the best way to do it, you should use a singleton of PDO2 class by example but it&#39;s a short code for help you

