In my opinion you have to change this one `x % 3 == 0` into `x / 3 == 0` 
(change the mode(%) to division(/) )
 

    int Amount_of_Numbers_Divisible_By_3(int x) 
    {
        int amount_of_numbers;
    
        if (x / 3 == 0) {
            amount_of_numbers++;
        } 
    
        return amount_of_numbers;
    }

In this case divisible numbers 3 (there are: 3,6,9);
             sum: 3+6+9=18

The problem is that your `amount_of_numbers` and `sum_of_numbers` are both stack variables, (which are unitialized). Even if you did zero-initialize them, rather than returning the true total they would only return 1 or 0 for `amount_of_numbers` and the number passed in for the `sum_of_numbers`. For your functions to work as they are you&#39;d need to pass in the total and modify or return the new value.

But lets talk about a better way to do this:

 * You know how many multiples of 3 there are between 1 and a given number by dividing it by 3
 * You know the sum of these numbers by finding the [triangular number](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangular_number) for that count multiplied by 3

So given a number `const int n` you can find:

 * `const auto amount_of_numbers = n / 3`
 * `const auto sum_of_numbers = 3 * (amount_of_numbers * (amount_of_numbers + 1) / 2)`

If you need that in a function you could do:

    pair&lt;int, int&gt; Numbers_Divisible_By_3(const int x) {
        const auto amount_of_numbers = x / 3;
        const auto sum_of_numbers = 3 * (amount_of_numbers * (amount_of_numbers + 1) / 2);

        return { amount_of_numbers, sum_of_numbers };
    }

If you wanted to find the results on numbers between 1 and 10 you could simply call: `Numbers_Divisible_By_3(10)`.

[&lt;kbd&gt;Live Example&lt;/kbd&gt;](http://ideone.com/GpsLh3)

all variables declared inside a function only have a scope pertinent inside the function. Outside it has no sense even if the variable name is the same somewhere else.  
So amount_of_numbers and sum_of_numbers must be passed as reference to the function:

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    #include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
    
    void Amount_of_Numbers_Divisible_By_3(int x, int&amp; amount_of_numbers);
    void Sum_of_Numbers_Divisible_By_3(int y, int&amp; sum_of_numbers);
    
    int main() {
    	int amount_variable=0, sum_variable=0;
    
    	for (int i = 1; i &lt; 10; i++) {
    		Amount_of_Numbers_Divisible_By_3(i, amount_variable);
    		Sum_of_Numbers_Divisible_By_3(i, sum_variable);
    	}
    	printf(&quot;There are %d numbers divisible by 3, sum of those numbers: %d\n&quot;, amount_variable, sum_variable);
    
    	return 0;
    }
    
    void Amount_of_Numbers_Divisible_By_3(int x, int &amp; amount_of_numbers)
    {
    
    	if (x % 3 == 0) {
    		amount_of_numbers++;
    	}
    }
    
    void Sum_of_Numbers_Divisible_By_3(int y, int &amp; sum_of_numbers)
    {
    
    	if (y % 3 == 0) {
    		sum_of_numbers += y;
    	}
    }

